docs.abstract: After losing tenants to revitalized downtowns over the last decade, developers are adding modern amenities to secluded campuses.
docs.snippet: After losing tenants to revitalized downtowns over the last decade, developers are adding modern amenities to secluded campuses.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Research Triangle Park in North Carolina opened in 1959, its bucolic setting was considered a major selling point. With office buildings hidden behind grassy meadows and swaths of pine forest, the quiet development was viewed as a perfect spot for the thinkers who went to work at companies like IBM and RTI International.

headline.main: The Suburban Office Park, an Aging Relic, Seeks a Comeback
headline.print_headline: Big-City Office Perks, Minus the Big City
